An unprecedented future.
JERUSALEM – With my almost 90 years of life now, I can't remember a time when the past was so insignificant in political decision-making.
None of the significant developments of the present were foreseen by anyone.
Experts did indeed examine the past, but as a result of their arrest, they were unable to derive the future from it in new paradigms.
Due to the dynamic complexity of the world today, in which the rapidly changing global economy, grounded in scientific evidence, has events more dependent on each other, we are unable to predict the future based on a linear extrapolation of the past.
The only certainty lies in the fact that the future will be determined by scientific progress and innovation, which cannot be known in advance.
As a result of these developments, the traditional power of states and state leaders is waning. In today's globalized economy, it is not politicians but innovators who wield the greatest influence.
The globalized economy affects all countries, and yet no single country can determine the outcome, because science and technology are borderless.
Multinational corporations operating globally want to carry out their business on the whole world, thereby suffering from sovereignty on the one hand, but on the other hand racism and prejudices as well as nationalism significantly weakened are.
As a result of this change, the fate of this world is now in the hands of a younger generation. They are more technologically savvy than their parents and connected to each other through social networks that transcend national borders, language barriers, or different forms of government.
The young founders of Facebook and Google wield greater global influence than many heads of state and generals.
These young people are also the spearhead of forming political protest movements.
The "Arab Spring", the tent demonstrations in Israel, Occupy Wall Street, and protests in Russia mark no battle of cultures, but a clash of generations.
The young generation knows that the way in which states and economies are currently run is unsuitable for the new times.
However, there are political "freeriders" who want to exploit this recent awakening. Nevertheless, not through the further development of an agenda of freedom, but through the introduction of new forms of coercion.
In the Arab world, Islamist extremists mainly appropriate the protests of the young generation and thereby steal the revolution from them.
Israel has positively responded to the will of the young generation, but cannot and must not intervene in the events of the Arab world.
We stand in solidarity with the young rebels and their legitimate yearning for freedom and basic rights, which should enable them to be heard, choose their political leadership and make a living.
Israelis are waiting for the day when their country will no longer be the only democracy in the region, because the existence as an island of prosperity in the middle of a sea of poverty is unnatural.
However, there is a serious concern that the politically well-organized extremists are trying to win control over less well-organized Liberals in elections and thereby prevent peace and stability.
Radical fundamentalists cannot offer real solutions to the region's fundamental problems.
The current social upheavals threaten their way of life, which includes the discrimination of women and a ban on modern education.
However, only fundamental reforms of traditional authority can pave the way towards freedom and growth.
Israel can serve as an example, when it comes to achieving economic well-being and social freedom, because its success is based on the fact that the country initially had nothing at all.
On our return to our homeland, we were rich in history, but poor in natural resources.
We could only fall back on our human capital.
That's why we invested in education and science. Therefore, we have the highest percentage of scientists and patents per capita today.
About 95 percent of our agriculture is based on high-tech.
We consume less water and yet have higher crop yields per square meter of cultivated area than any other country in the world.
What Israel achieves, others can also accomplish.
We are happy to offer our help wherever it is wanted.
Together and in peace with our neighbors, we can shape a region of hope, development, and success.
Above all, we must do everything within our power to end the conflict with the Palestinians.
Israel was not created to rule over another people, and that is also not Israel's destiny.
We are genuinely interested in the creation of a Palestinian state that exists peacefully and side by side with Israel - the democratic state of the Jewish people.
For us, peace is both a moral imperative and a national security strategy, because resolving the conflict would help to stabilise the region by neutralising the extremists who seek to manipulate civil movements to advance their radical agenda.
The international community can support these efforts by offering incentives to those countries that strive for freedom and progress.
At the same time, decisive and pioneering political measures must be taken against the extremists.
Especially Iran is a source of moral decay, where one promotes extremism and blocks reforms. One crushes legitimate protests of its own citizens and works against the brave Syrians who are currently fighting for their freedom.
In addition, Iran employs several proxies to target terrorism against moderate forces in the Palestinian Authority, in Lebanon and in Iraq.
If Iran succeeds in acquiring nuclear weapons, its leaders could shake the Middle East and further fuel extremism and violence.
Israel will defend itself if Iran continues to demand the destruction of Israel.
But not only Israel is threatened. Iran is a threat to peace and stability all over the world.
The democracies of this world have stated that they will not allow Iran to acquire nuclear weapons. It is their duty to fulfill this commitment before it is no longer possible.
Beyond these short-term challenges, we all have the duty to fundamentally change the way we prepare our children to deal with the world of today.
At a time when the past has become irrelevant for predicting the future, education must give all children the opportunity to realize their potential.
Teachers of today should motivate our children to creativity and innovation.
Self-realization is just as important as free speech.
I am writing this article at the age of 88, but not because I have learned from experience.
On the contrary: Experience is overvalued and frequently limits the courage needed to confront the future and create an unparalleled new world.
The future is already here. There's no sense in looking back.
